 overarching themes in the historical archaeology of the modern era, and postcolonial historical archaeology has repeatedly emphasized the complex two-way nature of colonial encounters. This volume examines common trajectories in indigenous colonial histories, and explores new ways to understand cultural contact, hybridization and power relations between indigenous peoples and colonial powers from the indigenous point of view. By bringing together a wide geographical range and combining multiple sources such as oral histories, historical records, and contemporary discourses with archaeological data, the volume finds new multivocal interpretations of colonial histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aIndigenous peoplesxColonization. 0aIndigenous peoplesxCultural assimilation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aArchaeological Data.  aColonial History.  aEuropean State Powers.  aHybridization and Power Relations.  aIndigenous Peoples.1 aAalto, Sirpa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayliss-Smith, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBethke, Brandi E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, Madeline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonishi, Shino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKylli, Ritva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalischke, LisaMarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulk, Inga-Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNurmi, Risto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOjala, Carl-Göst